  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Emerged as a concept during Prohibition era in the United States (1920s)\n- Initially related to concealing proceeds from illegal alcohol sales\n- Organized crime groups developed techniques to make illegal funds appear legitimate\n\n2. Initial Legal Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First US legislation requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Introduced mandatory reporting requirements for transactions over $10,000\n- Established framework for tracking potential money laundering activities\n\n3. International Progression\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global financial crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop anti-money laundering standards\n- United Nations conventions in 1988 and 2000 further criminalized money laundering internationally\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - First comprehensive federal statute criminalizing money laundering\n- Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988) - Expanded money laundering prohibitions\n- Patriot Act (2001) - Significantly enhanced reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n5. Contemporary Developments\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n- More sophisticated electronic monitoring technologies\n- Growing international cooperation in enforcement\n\nThese developments reflect an evolving legal approach to combating financial crimes.",
